    {
      "title": "Definition of Differential Equation",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Definition of a differential equation</strong></h3><p>An equation containing x,y &amp;$\\frac{dy}{dx},\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}},$, etc is called a differential equation. In other words, a differential equation is an equation that involves an independent variable (x), the depednent variables (y) &amp; the derivatives of the dependent variable $\\left( i.e.,\\,\\,\\frac{\\text{dy}}{\\text{dx}},\\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\text{d}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}},etc. \\right).$</p><p><strong>Example :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>(i)$\\frac{dy}{dx}+5x=0$</p><p>(ii) $\\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\text{d}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}+4\\text{x}\\left( \\text{sinx}+\\text{y} \\right)\\frac{\\text{dy}}{\\text{dx}}=0$</p><p>(iii) ${{\\left[ 1+{{\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\text{d}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}} \\right)}^{2}} \\right]}^{3/2}}=\\text{I}\\left( \\frac{\\text{dy}}{\\text{dx}}+\\text{ky} \\right)$</p><p>(iv) $1+{{\\left( \\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)}^{3}}=\\frac{{{d}^{5}}y}{d{{x}^{5}}}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd48c03b9dcaf1afea2d"
    },
    {
      "title": "Formation of Differential Equations",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Formation of Differential Equations&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Let f(x, y, a)=0 be a family of curves depending on one arbitrary constant a.</p><p>f(x, y, a)=0 ...(i)</p><p>Differentiating (1) with respect to x, we get</p><p>$\\text{P}\\left( \\text{x},\\text{y},{{\\text{y}}^{\\prime }},\\text{a} \\right)=0$ ...(ii)</p><p>Eliminating a from eq (1) and (2), we get an equation involving $x,y,{{y}^{\\prime }}.$. This is the required differential equation of the family of curves represented by (1). Similarly if the given differential equation has two arbitrary constants then we differentiable the given equation twice with respect to x. By eliminating the arbitrary constants from the given equation and the equations obtained by the differentiation, we get the required differential equations.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Find the differential equation from the family of straight lines which pass through the origin.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>The equation of the straight lines which pass through the origin</p><p>y = mx, where m is a parameter ...(1)</p><p>Differentiating (1) with respect to x</p><p>\\(\\frac{\\text{dy}}{\\text{dx}}=\\text{m}\\) ...(2)</p><p>Eliminating x from equation (1) and (2)&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Find the differential equation of the family of curves $y={{e}^{x}}(A\\cos x+B\\sin x)$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>\\(y={{e}^{x}}(A\\cos x+B\\sin x)\\) ...(1)</p><p>Differentiating with respect to x.</p><p>\\(\\frac{dy}{dx}={{e}^{x}}(A\\cos x+B\\sin x)+{{e}^{x}}(-A\\cos x+B\\sin x)\\)</p><p>\\(\\frac{dy}{dx}=y+{{e}^{x}}(-A\\sin x+B\\cos x)\\) ...(2)</p><p>Again differentiating with respect to x</p><p>\\(\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}-\\frac{dy}{dx}={{e}^{x}}(-A\\cos x-B\\sin x)+{{e}^{x}}(-A\\sin x+B\\cos x)=\\frac{dy}{dx}-y-y\\) [From Equation (2)]</p><p>or \\(\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}-2\\frac{dy}{dx}+2y=0;\\) which is the required differential equation.&nbsp;</p><p>Problem based on formation of differential eqaution</p><p><strong>Working Rules :&nbsp;</strong></p><ol><li>Write down the given equation</li><li>Differentiate the given equation with respect to independent variable x as many times as the number of arbitrary constants.</li><li>Eliminate the arbitrary constants from given equation and the equations obtained by differentiation.</li></ol><p><strong>Q) Obtain the differential equation of the family of curves represented by $y=A{{e}^{x}}+B{{e}^{-x}}+{{x}^{2}}\\text{,}$where A and B are arbitrary constants.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Given equation is $\\text{y}=\\text{A}{{\\text{e}}^{\\text{x}}}+\\text{B}{{\\text{e}}^{-\\text{x}}}+{{\\text{x}}^{2}}$ ...(1)</p><p>Differentiating w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$\\frac{dy}{dx}=A{{e}^{x}}-B{{e}^{-x}}+2x$ ...(2)</p><p>Again differentiating w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}=A{{e}^{x}}+B{{e}^{-x}}+2$ ...(3)</p><p>$(1)-(2)\\,\\,\\Rightarrow y-\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}={{x}^{2}}-2\\quad or,\\,\\,\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{{{d}^{2}}}-y+{{x}^{2}}-2=0$ ...(4)</p><p>(4) is the required differential equation, because it does not contain arbitrary constant A and B.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Q) Show that the function $y=(A+Bx){{e}^{3x}}$ is a solution of the differential equation $\\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\text{dx}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}\\,\\,-\\,\\,6\\,\\,\\frac{\\text{dy}}{\\text{dx}}+9\\,\\,\\text{y}=0$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Given, $\\mathrm{y}=(\\mathrm{A}+\\mathrm{Bx}) \\mathrm{e}^{3 \\mathrm{x}}$ ...(i)</p><p>Differentiating (i) w.r.t. x, we get $\\frac{dy}{dx}=\\text{B}{{\\text{e}}^{3x}}+3{{e}^{3x}}(A+Bx)$ ...(ii)</p><p>Differentiating (ii) w.r.t. x, we get $\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}=6\\text{B}{{\\text{e}}^{3x}}+9{{\\text{e}}^{3x}}(A+Bx)$ ...(iii)</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; \\therefore \\quad \\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}-6\\frac{dy}{dx}+9y=\\left\\{ 6B{{e}^{3x}}+9{{e}^{3x}}(A+Bx) \\right\\}-6\\,[B{{e}^{3x}}+3{{e}^{3x}}(A+Bx)\\}+\\left\\{ 9(A+Bx){{e}^{3x}} \\right.\\,\\,\\, \\\\ &amp; \\Rightarrow \\quad \\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}-6\\frac{dy}{dx}+9y=0 \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>So, $\\mathrm{y}=(\\mathrm{A}+\\mathrm{Bx}) \\mathrm{e}^{3 \\mathrm{x}}$ satisfies the given differential equation.</p><p>Hence, it is a solution of the given differential equation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Show that the differential equation of which $\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}} \\right)=c{{\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}}$ is the solution is $\\left( {{x}^{2}}-3x{{y}^{2}} \\right)dx=\\left( {{y}^{3}}-3{{x}^{2}}y \\right)dy$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>We have ${{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}}=c{{\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}}$</p><p>Differentiating (i) w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$2x-2y\\frac{dy}{dx}=2c\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)\\left( 2x+2y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)$</p><p>⇒ $\\left( x-y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)=2c\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)\\left( x+y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)$</p><p>From (i) and (ii), we have</p><p>$\\left( x-y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)=\\frac{2\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}} \\right)}{{{\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}}}\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)\\left( x+y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)$</p><p>[on substituting the value of c from (i) in (ii)]</p><p>⇒ $\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)\\left( x-y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)=2\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}} \\right)\\left( x+y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)$</p><p>⇒ \\(\\left. \\left\\{ x\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)-2x\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}} \\right) \\right\\}=\\frac{dy}{dx}\\{2y\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}} \\right))+y\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right) \\right\\}\\)</p><p>⇒ $\\left( 3x{{y}^{2}}-{{x}^{3}} \\right)=\\frac{dy}{dx}\\left( 3{{x}^{2}}y-{{y}^{3}} \\right)$</p><p>⇒ $\\left( {{x}^{3}}-3x{{y}^{2}} \\right)dx=\\left( {{y}^{3}}-3{{x}^{2}}y \\right)dy$</p><p>which is the given differential equation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) From the differential equation representing the family of curves y=A \\cos (x+B), where A and B are constants.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>We are given that $\\mathrm{y}=\\mathrm{A} \\cos (\\mathrm{x}+\\mathrm{B})$ ...(i)</p><p>[Since the given equation contains two arbitrary constants, we shall differentiate it two times and we shall get a differential equation of second order.]</p><p>Differentiate (i) w.r.t. x,. we get</p><p>$\\frac{dy}{dx}=-A\\sin (x+B)$ ...(ii)</p><p>$\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{{{d}^{2}}}=-A\\cos (A+B)$</p><p>⇒ \\(\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{{{d}^{2}}}=-y\\) [Using (i)]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Form the differential equation corresponding to ${{y}^{2}}$=a(b-x)(b+x) by eliminating a and b.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Given $\\mathrm{y}^2=\\mathrm{a}\\left(\\mathrm{b}^2-\\mathrm{x}^2\\right)$ ...(i)</p><p>[Since there are two arbitrary constants in the given equation, so we shall differentiate it two times and we shall get a differential equation of second order.]</p><p>Differentiating (i) w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$2y\\frac{dy}{dx}=-2ax\\Rightarrow y\\frac{dy}{dx}=-ax$ ...(ii)</p><p>Differentiating (ii) w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$\\text{y}\\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\text{d}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}+{{\\left( \\frac{\\text{dy}}{\\text{dx}} \\right)}^{2}}=-\\text{a}$ ...(iii)</p><p>From (ii) and (iii), we get</p><p>$x\\left[ y\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}+{{\\left( \\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)}^{2}} \\right]=y\\frac{dy}{dx}$</p><p>This is the required differential equation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) To form a differential equation from the equation ${{y}^{2}}$ </strong>= <strong>4ax where a is the parameter.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Given curve is ${{y}^{2}}$=4ax ...(i)</p><p>Differentiating (i) w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$2y\\frac{dy}{dx}=4a\\quad \\Rightarrow \\quad \\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{2a}{y}$ ...(ii)</p><p>Now eliminating a using (i) and (ii), we get</p><p>$y\\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{2x}\\quad \\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{. }\\quad \\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{y}{2x}$ ...(iii)</p><p>which is the required differential equation.</p><p><strong>To form a differential equation of a family of circles touching y-axis at origin.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\">&nbsp;</strong></p><p>The required equation of circles will be ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2gx=0\\,\\,(\\because f=c=0)$ where g is the parameter. That is for different values of g, we get different circles belonging to the family.</p><p>Differentiating (i) w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$2x+2y\\frac{dy}{dx}+2g=0$</p><p>Now eliminating 'g' using (i) and (ii), we get</p><p>${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2x\\left( -x-y\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)=0\\quad \\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{. }\\quad {{y}^{2}}-{{x}^{2}}-2xy\\frac{dy}{dx}=0$</p><p>which is the required differential equation.</p><p><strong>To form a differential equation of a family of circles having centre at origin.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\">&nbsp;</p><p>Let the equation of circle be</p><p>$\\mathrm{x}^2+\\mathrm{y}^2=\\mathrm{a}^2$ ...(i)</p><p>where a (radius) is the parameter.</p><p>Differentiating (i) w.r.t. x, we get</p><p>$2x+2y\\frac{dy}{dx}=0$</p><p>This is a differential equation for all the members of the</p><p>family &amp; it does not contain any parameter.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) If the differential equation whose equation represents the family $y={{e}^{3x}}+b{{e}^{x}}$, is $a\\,\\,\\,\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}+b\\frac{dy}{dx}+cy=0$, then a, b, c&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$y=a{{e}^{3x}}+b{{e}^{x}}$ ...(i)</p><p>Differentiating equation (i), we get</p><p>$\\frac{dy}{dx}=3a{{e}^{3x}}+b{{e}^{x}}$ ...(ii)</p><p>and $\\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\text{d}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}=9\\text{a}{{\\text{e}}^{3\\text{x}}}+\\text{b}{{\\text{e}}^{\\text{x}}}$ ...(iii)</p><p>Eliminating a and b from equation (i), (ii) &amp; (iii), we get</p><p>$\\frac{{{d}^{2}}y}{d{{x}^{2}}}-\\frac{4y}{dx}-3y=0\\Rightarrow a=1,b=-4,c=3$</p><p><strong>Note : </strong>The order of differential equation (of family of curves with n constants) is equal to n. But sometimes the order of the differential equation can be find on the basis of its solution. The order of differential equation is equal to the number of constants involved in the solution (in reduced condition).</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd48c03b9dcaf1afea2e"
    }
